\begin_layout Standard
Smoothed particle hydrodynamics (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{sph}
\end_layout

\end_inset

), the first modern meshless method, was developed in 1977 for use in astrophysi
cs problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lucy-numerical-1977,gingold-smoothed-1977"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{sph}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method, fluid motion is represented using moving particles smoothed by
 kernel functions, which contrasts with mesh-based methods in which the
 fluid moves through stationary mesh elements (Eulerian), the mesh moves
 with the fluid (Lagrangian), or the two are combined (Arbitrary Lagrangian-Eule
rian 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hirt-arbitrary-1974"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{sph}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method has been applied to astrophysics, fluid dynamics, explosion mechanics,
 solid mechanics, heat conduction and magnetohydrodynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu-smoothed-2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Boundary conditions are difficult to enforce using the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{sph}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method, and as such many of the applications include unbounded problems.
 The reproducing kernel particle method developed in 1995 includes corrections
 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{sph}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu-reproducing-1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and has been applied to similar problems.
 Other meshless methods for fluid flow and solid dynamics include the finite
 point method developed in 1996 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "onate-finite-1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and the point interpolation method developed in 2001 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu-point-2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collocation approach, in which the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pde}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is enforced at collocation points to find the coefficients of a basis function
 expansion, was developed in 1990 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kansa-multiquadrics-1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and has been applied to a diverse set of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pde}
\end_layout

\end_inset

s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fasshauer-solving-1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, including fluid dynamics, heat conduction, convection-diffusion, transport,
 and diffusion problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chen-recent-2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 With the original global basis functions, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pde}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 solution matrix is dense and difficult to solve.
 The accuracy of the method increases as the basis functions become essentially
 flat, but this makes the linear system severely ill-conditioned 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fornberg-runge-2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For advection problems, the streaming operator cannot be easily stabilized.
 Despite these drawbacks, the collocation method is simple to apply and
