Meshless methods can be divided into those that use the strong form and
 the weak form of the partial differential equation (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pde}
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 The most common strong-form method is the collocation approach developed
 by Kansa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kansa-multiquadrics-1990,fasshauer-solving-1996"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, in which the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pde}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is enforced at collocation points to find the coefficients of a basis function
 expansion.
 The accuracy of the method increases as the basis functions become essentially
 flat, but this makes the linear system severely ill-conditioned 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fornberg-runge-2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In addition, spatially-dependent 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{pde}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 coefficients (such as the cross sections in the neutron transport equation)
 present unresolved issues for strong-form solutions.
 Evaluation of the coefficients at the collocation points 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dehghan-meshless-2009,zhao-second-2013,wang-meshless-2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 makes an implicit assumption that the coefficients are continuous and have
 small gradients, as the coefficients between these points are not considered.
 Localization of the basis functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nguyen-meshless-2008"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, such as through domain decomposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "li-domain-2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, makes the opposite assumption that coefficients are piecewise constant
 and requires that the basis functions be tailored to the discontinuities.
 For a discretization with arbitrary basis functions and coefficients with
 discontinuities, neither method is as generally applicable as an appropriate
 approximation using the weak form of the transport equation.
 
\end_layout

