 radiative transport and conductive heat transfer equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kindelan-application-2010,sadat-meshless-2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, including the use of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with moving least squares (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mls}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) basis functions and weight functions skewed along the upwind direction
 for stabilization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu-meshless-2007"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which is similar to the spatial discretization used here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset

There are a few important distinctions between the radiative transfer and
 neutron transport equation.
 While the radiative transfer equation does include frequency (or energy)
 dependence that can be converted into a multigroup form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "turpault-consistent-2005"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, this is often neglected for the gray approximation.
 Some common approximations made in radiative transfer meshless methods,
 such as energy independence, homogeneous materials and directionally-dependent
 weak-form integrals, would be unsuitable for neutron transfer.
 For this dissertation, the energy dependence is discretized using the multigrou
p approximation, the materials are assumed to be spatially dependent and
 the weak-form integration is performed independent of discrete direction
 dependence.
 This allows for reasonably efficient solution of the transport equation
 for realistic problems with energy dependence and a large number of angular
 directions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset

The neutron transport equation has not been extensively studied using meshless
 methods.
 In 2017, Kashi et.
 al used meshless basis functions to solve the weak transport equation inside
 each homogeneous element in a two-dimensional Cartesian finite element
 mesh, producing a method very similar to the discontinuous finite element
 method (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{dfem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) but with basis functions commonly used in meshless methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kashi-mesh-2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Despite the differences in the source term and energy dependence, many
 of the meshless techniques used in other transport problems should be directly
 applicable to neutron transport.
 The neutron diffusion equation is stable and simple to solve using meshless
 methods.
 The element-free Galerkin method with moving least squares basis and weight
 functions has been applied to one group diffusion with spatially-varying
 cross sections in one and two dimensions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rokrok-element-2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The multigroup diffusion problem has been solved using the collocation
 method with global basis functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tanbay-numerical-2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset

In standard deterministic radiation transport methods, material properties
 are often assumed to be constant within each cell.
 Monte Carlo methods with delta tracking 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "brown-direct-2003"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 or functional expansion tallies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ellis-preliminary-2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 more accurately account for spatially varying cross sections but at a high
 computational cost.
 One treatment for spatially varying cross sections in a deterministic multiphys
ics code is an averaging of the cross section in each cell using a numerical
 quadrature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "schunert-approximate-2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, which does not explicitly guarantee global particle conservation.
 The cross section integration methods presented in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:cross-section-discretization"

\end_inset

 do guarantee particle conservation and could be used in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{dfem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 codes without significant modification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset

Another area where many deterministic radiation transport codes struggle
 is curved surface representation.
 Method of characteristics codes can exactly represent curved surfaces but
 become computationally expensive for three-dimensional simulations.
 During the sweep process of a 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{dfem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 transport code, an element with a curved surface may have a reentrant condition
 on the boundary, which leads to an indeterminate sweep order.
 A few methods to accurately account for higher-order surfaces include choosing
 a single outward normal for each surface 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "adams-discontinuous-2001"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, temporarily splitting the high-order cells a direction-dependent fashion
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu-discrete-2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, solving for a second-order source on a first-order mesh 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "schunert-approximate-2017"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and assembling and directly solving the full 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{fem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "woods-high-2016"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 In the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method with the cross sections in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:cross-section-discretization"

\end_inset

, curved surfaces inside the domain are accounted for in the integration
 step, not the meshing or transport steps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method used here is very similar mathematically to solving the radiation
 transport equation using a continuous finite element method (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{cfem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

