\begin_layout Subsection
Weak form of the transport equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:weak-form-transport"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weak form of the transport equation is derived by multiplying the strong-for
m equations [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong"

\end_inset

] by a series of weight functions 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 and integrating over the volume of support for these weight functions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{j}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:weak-prelim"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{L}^{w}\psi\right)_{j,n,g}^{*} & =\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\psi_{n,g}dV+\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\Sigma_{t;g}\psi_{n,g}dV,\label{eq:weak-streaming}\\
\left(\mathcal{S}^{w}\phi\right)_{j,\ell,g}^{m} & =\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\Sigma_{s;\ell,g'\to g}\phi_{\ell,g'}^{m}dV,\label{eq:weak-scattering}\\
\left(\mathcal{F}^{w}\phi\right)_{j,\ell,g}^{m} & =\delta_{\ell,0}\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\chi_{g}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\nu_{g'}\Sigma_{f;g'}\phi_{0,g'}^{0}dV.\label{eq:weak-fission}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The streaming term is integrated by parts to produce surface integrals for
 the outgoing flux and the incoming flux,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{L}^{w}\psi\right)_{j,n,g} & =\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}>0}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right)\psi_{n,g}w_{j}dS-\int_{V_{j}}\psi_{n,g}\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}dV+\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\Sigma_{t;g}\psi_{n,g}dV,\\
\left(q\right)_{j,n,g} & =\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}<0}\left|\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right|\psi_{n,g}^{inc}w_{j}dS+\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}q_{n,g}dV.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Reflection is separated from the known incoming angular flux to get a reflective
 boundary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset

 that is a applied to the unknown angular flux on the boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{R}^{w}\psi^{b}\right)_{j,n,g} & =\rho\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}<0}\left|\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right|\psi_{n_{r},g}w_{j}dS.\label{eq:weak-reflection}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 denotes the operators specific to the weak form of the transport equation.
 The operator forms of the weak steady-state and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-eigenvalue transport equations that include the reflection term are
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:weak-operator"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}^{w}\psi & =\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{w}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{w}+\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{w}\right)\bm{\phi}+q,\\
\mathcal{L}^{w}\psi & =\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{w}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{w}+\frac{1}{k}\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{w}\right)\bm{\phi},
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where the augmented solution is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\phi}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\phi\\
\psi^{b}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the augmented operators are 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:augmented-operators"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{w} & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mathcal{M} & \mathcal{R}^{w}\end{array}\right],\\
\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{w} & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mathcal{S}^{w} & 0\\
0 & \mathcal{I}^{b}
\end{array}\right],\\
\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{w} & =\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mathcal{F}^{w} & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{b}$
\end_inset

 is the values of the angular flux on the boundary and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}^{b}$
\end_inset

 is the identity operator for this quantity, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{I}^{b}\psi^{b}=\psi^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-prelim"

\end_inset

 represent an independent set of linear equations that can be spatially
 discretized by inserting a basis function expansion of the angular flux
 and its moments.
 For the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method, such a discretization produces oscillations caused by advection
 in the streaming operator [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-streaming"

\end_inset

].
 Stabilization added to the streaming operator helps prevent these non-physical
 oscillations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
SUPG stabilization of the transport equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supg-stabilization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While advection in a continuous Petrov-Galerkin method creates oscillations,
 diffusion dampens them.
 This property motivates the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method, which adds numerical diffusion in the streamline direction by modifying
 the advection term, using this modification to change to the weight functions
 appropriately and applying the altered weight functions to the entire transport
 equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fries-review-2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive an appropriate diffusion term to add to the advection operator,
 a diffusion operator is applied to the angular flux, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\bm{\nabla}\cdot\left(\bm{D}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\right)\psi_{n,g}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the diffusion tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{D}=\bm{\Omega}_{n}\bm{\Omega}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This is converted to weak form by multiplying by the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 and integrating by parts,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & -\int_{S_{j}}\left[\bm{n}\cdot\left(\bm{D}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\right)\psi_{n,g}\right]w_{j}dS\nonumber \\
 & \qquad+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\psi_{n,g}\right)\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)dV=0.\label{eq:weak-supg-diffusion-comp}
\end{align}

\end_inset

The process of adding the volume integral in this diffusion equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-supg-diffusion-comp"

\end_inset

] to the streaming operator in the weak transport equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-streaming"

\end_inset

], 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\psi_{n,g}\right)\left(w_{j}+\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)dV,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be replicated by augmenting the weight functions in Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-streaming"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-fission"

\end_inset

 by the streaming operator, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{w}_{j,n}=w_{j}+\tau\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}.\label{eq:augmented-weight}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a proportionality constant with units of length that is discussed in
 more detail in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supg-stabilization-implementation"

\end_inset

.
 The augmented weight functions in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:augmented-weight"

\end_inset

 are used everywhere, not only for the streaming term.
 Because of this, the equations retain the properties of a Petrov-Galerkin
 method, specifically that the exact solution to the transport equation
 fulfills the discretized equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 transport equations are derived by replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{w}_{j,n}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-prelim"

\end_inset

 and integrating the streaming operator by parts for only the 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 term from the augmented weight function [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:augmented-weight"

\end_inset

], which leaves the surface integrals unchanged.
 The equations become
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:supg"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{L}^{u}\psi\right)_{j,n,g} & =\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}>0}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right)\psi_{n,g}w_{j}dS+\int_{V_{j}}\left[-\psi_{n,g}+\tau\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\psi_{n,g}\right]\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)dV\nonumber \\
 & \qquad+\int_{V_{j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}\Sigma_{t;g}\psi_{n,g}dV,\label{eq:supg-streaming}\\
\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}^{u}\phi\right)_{j,n,g} & =\sum_{\ell=0}^{L}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\int_{V_{j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}\Sigma_{s;\ell,g'\to g}\phi_{\ell,g'}^{m}dV,\\
\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{F}^{u}\phi\right)_{j,n,g} & =\frac{1}{4\pi}\int_{V_{j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}\chi_{g}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\nu_{g'}\Sigma_{f;g'}\phi_{0,g'}^{0}dV,\\
\left(q^{u}\right)_{j,n,g} & =\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}<0}\left|\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right|\psi_{n,g}^{ext}w_{j}dS+\int_{V_{j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}q_{n,g}dV,\label{eq:supg-source}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 superscript denotes operators specific to the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equations.
 The resulting addition to the streaming term in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:supg-streaming"

\end_inset

 applies numerical diffusion preferentially to neutrons whose direction
 of flight 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}_{n}$
\end_inset

 is codirectional with the gradient of the angular flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\nabla}\psi_{n,g}$
\end_inset

.
 Due to the directional dependence of the weight functions, the scattering
 and fission operators are combined with the moment-to-discrete operator.
 The decoupling of these operators is discussed in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:supg-stabilization-implementation"

\end_inset

.
 The reflection operator does not change from the unstabilized form of the
 equations [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-reflection"

\end_inset

].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Petrov-Galerkin form of the transport equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:petrov-galerkin"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To complete the discretization of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

-stabilized transport equations [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:supg"

\end_inset

], free variables are added to match the number of constraints.
 The Petrov-Galerkin method uses functional expansions for the angular flux
 and its moments as the unknown variables for the weak form of the transport
 equation, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:basis-expansions"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\psi_{n,g}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{J}\alpha_{i,n,g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right),\label{eq:angular-expansion}\\
\phi_{\ell,g}^{m}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{J}\beta_{i,\ell,g}^{m}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right),\label{eq:moment-expansion}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

with the basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, the angular flux expansion coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i,n,g}$
\end_inset

 and the moment expansion coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i,\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Using the definition of the spherical harmonics moments in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:spherical-harmonics-moments"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i,\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

 can be defined in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i,n,g}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta_{i,\ell,g}^{m}\equiv\sum_{n=1}^{N}w_{n}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)\alpha_{i,n,g}.\label{eq:coefficient-relation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This allows direct conversion between the two types of coefficients.
 Substituting the basis expansions into Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:supg"

\end_inset

, the operators of the transport equation become 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:supg-petrov-galerkin"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\alpha\right)_{j,n,g} & =\sum_{i=1}^{J}\left[\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}>0}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right)b_{i}w_{j}dS+\int_{V_{i,j}}\left(-b_{i}+\tau\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}b_{i}\right)\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)dV\right.\nonumber \\
 & \qquad\left.+\int_{V_{i,j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}\Sigma_{t;g}b_{i}dV\right]\alpha_{i,n,g},\label{eq:streaming-petrov}\\
\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}^{p}\beta\right)_{j,n,g} & =\sum_{\ell=0}^{L}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)\sum_{i=1}^{J}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\left(\int_{V_{i,j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}\Sigma_{s;\ell,g'\to g}b_{i}dV\right)\beta_{i,\ell,g'}^{m},\\
\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{F}^{p}\beta\right)_{j,n,g} & =\frac{1}{4\pi}\sum_{i=1}^{J}\left(\int_{V_{i,j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}\chi_{g}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\nu_{g'}\Sigma_{f;g'}b_{i}dV\right)\beta_{i,\ell,g'}^{m},\\
\left(\mathcal{R}^{p}\alpha^{b}\right)_{j,n,g} & =\rho\sum_{i=1}^{J}\left(\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}<0}\left|\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right|b_{i}w_{j}dS\right)\alpha_{i,n_{r},g}^{b},\label{eq:reflective-petrov}\\
\left(q^{p}\right)_{j,n,g} & =\int_{\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}<0}\left|\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}\right|\psi_{n,g}^{ext}w_{j}dS+\int_{V_{j}}\tilde{w}_{j,n}q_{n,g}dV,\label{eq:source-petrov}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i,j}$
\end_inset

 is the intersection of the support region for the basis function 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 and weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:meshless-integration"

\end_inset

 for details).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 superscript denotes the operators specific to the Petrov-Galerkin form
 of the equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operators for the Petrov-Galerkin equations are applied directly to
 the expansion coefficients instead of to physical flux values, which changes
 Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-operator"

\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:petrov-galerkin-operator"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}^{p}\alpha & =\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{p}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{p}+\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{p}\right)\bm{\beta}+q^{p},\\
\mathcal{L}^{p}\alpha & =\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{p}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{p}+\frac{1}{k}\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{p}\right)\bm{\beta},
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with the same augments an in Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:augmented-operators"

\end_inset

 and the augmented coefficients
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\beta}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\beta\\
\alpha^{b}
\end{array}\right].
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:supg-petrov-galerkin"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:petrov-galerkin-operator"

\end_inset

 represent a fully-determined linear system of equations, meaning a standard
 linear or eigenvalue solver could solve these directly.
 However, iterative schemes such as those in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:iterative-schemes"

\end_inset

 can significantly reduce the cost of solving the transport equation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Iterative schemes for the neutron transport equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:iterative-schemes"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reduce the number of unknowns, the coefficients for the moments of the
 angular flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, are chosen as the solution variable for the transport equation.
 This assumes that the directional dependence of the exact angular flux
 can be accurately represented in terms of a spherical harmonics expansion,
 which is the case for a solution with limited anisotropy.
 The reflective boundary adds additional solution variables for the angular
 flux expansion coefficients at the boundary, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{b}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few additional operators are needed to remove the angular flux coefficients
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 from the the operator form of the transport equation.
 Using the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}\alpha=\alpha^{b}$
\end_inset

 that removes non-boundary terms from 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, augmented forms of the discrete-to-moment operator are defined as
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bm{\mathcal{D}} & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{D}\\
\mathcal{\mathcal{A}}
\end{array}\right],\\
\bm{\mathcal{D}}_{q} & =\left[\begin{array}{c}
\mathcal{D}\\
0
\end{array}\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To isolate the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 values, the inverse of the streaming operator, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

, is applied to Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:petrov-galerkin-operator"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\alpha & =\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\right)^{-1}\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{p}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{p}+\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{p}\right)\bm{\beta}+\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\right)^{-1}q^{p},\\
\alpha & =\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\right)^{-1}\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{p}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{p}+\frac{1}{k}\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{p}\right)\bm{\beta}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{p}$
\end_inset

 operators for each group and direction are independent and the inversion
 can be done independently (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:transport-sweep-operator"

\end_inset

).
 Applying the discrete-to-moment operators to both sides of these equations
 and rearranging the terms results in a form of each of the equations that
 is suitable for Krylov iterative methods,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:operator-petrov"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\left[\bm{\mathcal{I}}-\bm{\mathcal{D}}\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\right)^{-1}\bm{\mathcal{M}}^{p}\left(\bm{\mathcal{S}}^{p}+\bm{\mathcal{F}}^{p}\right)\right]\bm{\beta}=\bm{\mathcal{D}}_{q}\left(\mathcal{L}^{p}\right)^{-1}q^{p},\label{eq:operator-steady-petrov}\\
