LatexCommand label
name "eq:strong-basis"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathcal{L}^{tb}\alpha\right)_{j,n,g} & \sum_{i}\left[\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right)+\overline{\Sigma}_{t;i,g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right)\right]\alpha_{i,n,g},\\
\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}^{tb}\beta\right)_{j,n,g} & =\sum_{\ell=0}^{L}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)\sum_{i=1}^{J}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\overline{\Sigma}_{s;i,\ell,g'\to g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right)\beta_{i,\ell,g'}^{m},\\
\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{F}^{tb}\beta\right)_{j,n,g} & =\frac{1}{4\pi}\sum_{i=1}^{J}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\overline{\Sigma}_{f;i,g'\to g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right)\beta_{i,\ell,g'}^{m}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $th$
\end_inset

 denotes operators specific to the basis-weighted collocation operators.
 The boundary conditions from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-boundary-point"

\end_inset

 still apply.
 Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-basis"

\end_inset

 also carry no guarantee of particle conservation but do include integral
 weighting of the cross sections.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:vera1e-strong"

\end_inset

, this is shown to improve the result of the strong-form equation for a
 problem with heterogeneous materials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the strong-form equations, the boundary condition is not incorporated
 directly into the transport equation.
 Instead, the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{j}$
\end_inset

 are separated into those on the problem boundary and those inside the problem
 domain.
 The boundary condition is applied to every boundary point on upwind boundaries,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}<0$
\end_inset

, while the transport equation is applied to every point inside the domain
 and every boundary point not on upwind boundaries, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{n}>0$
\end_inset

.
 The iterative methods for the weak form [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:operator-petrov"

\end_inset

] apply for these equations with the strong-form operators as well, with
 the distinction that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operator applies the boundary condition for the upwind boundary points
 [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-boundary-point"

\end_inset

].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Functions for meshless methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:meshless-functions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basis functions and weight functions that provide the functional expansions
 and test functions in the transport equations [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:supg-petrov-galerkin"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-point"

\end_inset

] have not been defined.
 The two requirements discussed in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:particle-balance"

\end_inset

 for the weak form to satisfy the conservation equation are that the weight
 functions sum to one [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weight-function-sum"

\end_inset

] and that the basis functions can accurately represent the exact solution.
 A third property that makes computation much more efficient is if the radius
 of support for the basis and weight functions is compact.
 A compact function has a value of zero outside of its support region.
 This limits the number of basis functions that overlap with each weight
 function and the number of functions with a nonzero value at any given
 point, which makes the integrals in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equations tractable and leads to sparse matrices for the streaming operator
 (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:iterative-schemes"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Radial basis functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:radial-basis-functions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common class of functions used in meshless methods is the radial basis
 function (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 The value of an 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 depends only on the distance traversed by the input vector, regardless
 of the number of dimensions.
 An example of a 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with the dimensionless distance 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the Gaussian function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\text{gauss}}\left(r\right)=e^{-r^{2}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To make this 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 compact, the value of the Gaussian function can be decreased by a constant
 to have a zero value at and after a finite value 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of the dimensionless radial value 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{\text{comp gauss}}\left(r\right)=\begin{cases}
\frac{e^{-r^{2}}-e^{R^{2}}}{1-e^{-R^{2}}}, & r<R,\\
0, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}\label{eq:compact-gaussian}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A good choice for 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 may be around 
\begin_inset Formula $R=5.0$
\end_inset

, which limits the discontinuity in the derivative at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=R$
\end_inset

 to around 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-10}$
\end_inset

.
 When integrating the basis and weight functions, this discontinuity can
 decrease the accuracy of the integration.
 Other popular 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

s include the multiquadric and inverse multiquadric functions,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\Gamma_{\text{mult}}\left(r\right)=\sqrt{1+r^{2}},\label{eq:multiquadric}\\
\Gamma_{\text{inv mult}}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{1+r^{2}}}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset

These functions are shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:global-rbfs"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There also exist compact 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 functions with no derivative at the edge of the support radius, such as
 the Wendland functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wendland-error-1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Gamma_{x,y}\left(r\right)=\begin{cases}
\gamma_{x,y}\left(r\right) & r\leq1,\\
0, & \text{otherwise},
\end{cases}\label{eq:wendland-base}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where a few of the functions are defined as
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:wendland"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\gamma_{1,1}\left(r\right) & =\left(1-r\right)^{3}\left(1+3r\right),\label{eq:wendland11}\\
\gamma_{1,2}\left(r\right) & =\left(1-r\right)^{5}\left(1+5r+8r^{2}\right),\\
\gamma_{1,3}\left(r\right) & =\left(1-r\right)^{7}\left(1+7r+19r^{2}+21r^{3}\right),\\
\gamma_{3,1}\left(r\right) & =\left(1-r\right)^{4}\left(4r+1\right),\\
\gamma_{3,2}\left(r\right) & =\left(1-r\right)^{6}\left(3+18r+35r^{2}\right),\\
\gamma_{3,3}\left(r\right) & =\left(1-r\right)^{8}\left(1+8r+25r^{2}+32r^{3}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

These functions are computationally inexpensive to evaluate, but unlike
 the Gaussian, multiquadric, and inverse multiquadric functions, they have
 limited smoothness (i.e.
 a limited number of continuous derivatives).
 For the weak transport equation, which only contains first derivatives,
 this is not a practical limitation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

s can be used directly as basis or weight functions in the Petrov-Galerkin
 method from Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:petrov-galerkin"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
g_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\Gamma\left(\epsilon_{i}d\left(\bm{x},\bm{x}_{i}\right)\right),\label{eq:rbf-basis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is some distance measure such as the Euclidean distance,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{L_{2}}\left(\bm{x},\bm{y}\right)=\left\Vert \bm{x}-\bm{y}\right\Vert .
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 distance creates functions that are radially symmetric about the center
 of the function at 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 distance would create a square region of support.
 For the following chapters, the 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 distance is used in all cases.
 These functions have the shape parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

, which controls the support radius of the function.
 If the support radius of an 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{sup}$
\end_inset

 [e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{sup}=1$
\end_inset

 for the example in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:wendland-base"

\end_inset

] and the desired support radius of the basis or weight function is 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

, the shape parameter is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{i}=\frac{r_{sup}}{r_{i}}.\label{eq:rbf-shape}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The gradient of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is taken using the chain rule,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\nabla}g_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\epsilon_{i}\left[\bm{\nabla}d\left(\bm{x},\bm{x}_{i}\right)\right]\circ\left[\bm{\nabla}\Gamma\left(\epsilon_{i}d\left(\bm{x},\bm{x}_{i}\right)\right)\right],\label{eq:rbf-derivative}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 denotes the Hadamard (or entrywise) product.
 Sets of radial basis functions do not generally form a partition of unity,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{there exists }\bm{x}\text{ such that }\sum_{i=1}^{I}g_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)\neq1,\label{eq:rbf-partition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means that they do not meet the desired requirements for particle
 conservation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Moving least squares functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:moving-least-squares"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The moving least squares (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mls}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) method transforms a meshless basis into a new basis that can represent
 a certain order of polynomials exactly.
 When used for interpolation, the method minimizes the error of the function
 with respect to given values in a least-squares sense.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mls}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 functions are defined as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "liu-introduction-2005"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:mls-value"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\bm{p}^{\top}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{A}^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{B}_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bm{p}^{\top}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\left[\begin{array}{ccccccccccc}
1 & x & y & z & xy & xz & yz & x^{2} & y^{2} & z^{2} & \dots\end{array}\right],\\
\bm{A}\left(\bm{x}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}g_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{p}\left(\bm{x}_{i}\right)\bm{p}^{\top}\left(\bm{x}_{i}\right),\\
\bm{B}_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)=g_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{p}\left(\bm{x}_{i}\right).
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 functions are the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 weighting functions from the other meshless basis.
 The action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is to normalize the value of the basis functions at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}$
\end_inset

 so the new basis can represent functions in the set of polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{p}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 exactly.
 When multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{B}_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, the function represents the value for the new, normalized basis 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Derivatives of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mls}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 functions can be taken using the product rule, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:mls-derivative"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial h_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}}=\frac{\partial\bm{p}^{\top}\left(\bm{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}}\bm{A}^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{B}_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)+\bm{p}^{\top}\left(\bm{x}\right)\frac{\partial\bm{A}^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}}\bm{B}_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)+\bm{p}^{\top}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{A}^{-1}\left(\bm{x}\right)\frac{\partial\bm{B}_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}},
\end{equation}

