\begin_layout Standard
The centers of the basis and weight functions can be placed independently
 of one another and of the problem geometry, with a few caveats.
 For accurate representation of the solution, a higher concentration of
 centers should be placed in areas where high gradients are expected.
 If the weight function centers are placed too close together, the equations
 are no longer be independent and the system is underdetermined, while if
 the basis centers are placed too close together, the unknown variables
 are no longer be independent and the system is overdetermined.
 To prevent these issues, the code checks each basis and weight function
 center for other centers that are too close.
 This is quantified for each center by comparing the radius of the meshless
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the distance to the nearest other center 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}^{\text{nearest}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is quantified in the code by a ratio of these two quantities, which
 should be larger than a predefined tolerance 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\epsilon<\frac{d_{i}^{\text{nearest}}}{r_{i}},
\]

\end_inset

which for these calculations is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=10^{-3}$
\end_inset

.
 For randomized points, this tolerance may need to be increased to properly
 protect against an ill-conditioned set of points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The algorithm to calculate the radii of the basis and weight functions is
 listed in Alg.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:radius-calculation"

\end_inset

.
 The purpose of the algorithm is to ensure that at the center of each basis
 or weight function, at least 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 nearest points have a nonzero value.
 If the point spacing is not too irregular (e.g.
 sets of isolated points that don't 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

see
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 other any other sets), this also ensures basis and weight function coverage
 throughout the problem domain.
 The connectivity of the chosen points and radii is calculated using a k-d
 tree 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bentley-multidimensional-1975"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 from nanoflann 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blanco-nanoflann:-2014"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 To find which basis functions overlap with each weight function, the weight
 function radius is added to the maximum basis function radius in the problem
 and a radius search is performed to find candidates for intersection, which
 are then individually checked for actual intersection.
 
\end_layout

