\begin_layout Subsubsection
SUPG stabilization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:supg-stabilization-implementation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameter that controls the addition of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 stabilization into the problem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:augmented-weight"

\end_inset

, is chosen to be weight-function dependent (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\to\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

) according to the radius of the weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau_{j}=cr_{j},\label{eq:tau-radius}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is user-defined constant.
 With the shape parameter from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rbf-shape"

\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 value and derivative from Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rbf-basis"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rbf-derivative"

\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

 value from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:tau-radius"

\end_inset

 with a dimensionless support radius of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{sup}=1$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

-augmented weight function [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:augmented-weight"

\end_inset

] becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{w}_{j,n}=\Gamma\left(\epsilon_{j}d\left(\bm{x},\bm{x}_{i}\right)\right)+c\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\left(\left[\bm{\nabla}d\left(\bm{x},\bm{x}_{i}\right)\right]\circ\left[\bm{\nabla}\Gamma\left(\epsilon_{j}d\left(\bm{x},\bm{x}_{i}\right)\right)\right]\right).\label{eq:explicit-supg-weight}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:explicit-supg-weight"

\end_inset

 shows that for the of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:tau-radius"

\end_inset

, the function-to-derivative ratio in the stabilized weight function becomes
 independent of the weight function radius 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 A constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 would add comparatively more numerical diffusion for weight functions with
 smaller radii.
 This does mean that the condition for conservation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:augmented-weight-function-sum"

\end_inset

] is not preserved, as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=1}^{J}\tau_{j}\bm{\Omega}_{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\neq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in general, even where Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weight-function-sum"

\end_inset

 holds.
 However, in empirical tests, the weight function-dependent 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

 shows better performance and convergence for problems with varying radii
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j}$
\end_inset

 than a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In both the full [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:full-transport"

\end_inset

] and basis [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:basis-transport"

\end_inset

] fully-discretized equations, the moment-to-discrete operator attached
 to the scattering, fission and implicitly the source can be separated by
 separating the terms including 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 from the terms included in the transport equation without 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The summation of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 terms is then performed using a modified moment-to-discrete operator.
 This adds an additional index for the gradient terms, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 in the following equations.
 For example, for the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

full
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cross section equations, the scattering term becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathcal{S}^{d}\beta\right)_{j,n,g,d}=\begin{cases}
\sum_{i=1}^{J}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\overline{\Sigma}_{s;i,j,\ell,g'\to g}^{0}\beta_{i,\ell,g'}^{m}, & d=0,\\
\sum_{i=1}^{J}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\left(\overline{\bm{\Sigma}}_{s;i,j,\ell,g'\to g}^{1}\right)_{d}\beta_{i,\ell,g'}^{m}, & d=1,2,3.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the moment-to-discrete operator becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathcal{M}^{d}\beta\right)_{j,n,g}=\sum_{\ell=0}^{L}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)\sum_{d=0}^{3}f_{d}\tilde{\beta}_{j,\ell,g,d}^{m},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\beta}_{j,\ell,g,d}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is the result of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}^{d}$
\end_inset

 scattering operator and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{d}=\begin{cases}
1, & d=0,\\
\tau\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)_{d}, & d=1,2,3.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

With these definitions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}^{d}\mathcal{S}^{d}\beta=\left(\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}^{p}\right)\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The results for the fission cross term directly follow.
 This same method can be applied to the volume part of the source term,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(q_{V}^{d}\right)_{j,\ell,g,d}^{m}=\begin{cases}
\overline{Q}_{j,\ell,g}^{m,0}, & d=0,\\
\left(\overline{\bm{Q}}_{j,\ell,g}^{m,1}\right)_{d}, & d=1,2,3.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the same moment-to-discrete operator.
 These optimizations cut down on unnecessary computational cost in the scatterin
g, fission and internal source operators.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Streaming and collision operator
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:transport-sweep-operator"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operator in both the weak and strong forms [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:streaming-petrov"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-point-streaming"

\end_inset

, respectively] represents the application of a set of independent, sparse
 matrices for each direction 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and energy group 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, with weighted equations corresponding to the rows.
 The number of nonzero elements in each row 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is the number of basis functions that intersect with the applicable weight
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 operator, or the inverse of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operator, is equivalent to the solution of the system
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\alpha=q\label{eq:linv-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 given the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 The sparse 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 matrix reduces storage cost and permits the use of sparse linear algebra
 packages to solve Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:linv-system"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Linear solver packages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several solvers from Trilinos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heroux-overview-2005"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 are implemented to solve the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 linear problem in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:linv-system"

\end_inset

.
 The KLU solver from Amesos uses the LU decomposition to directly solve
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 problem.
 The direct solver is much more expensive in memory and computational cost
 than iterative solvers and is not generally needed for the weak-form equations
 with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 stabilization.
 The strong-form equations and the weak-form equations without 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 stabilization have far worse conditioning without this diffusive stabilization
 and generally do not work with iterative solvers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Pseudo-Block generalized minimal residual (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) solver from the Belos package is used for iterative solution of the linear
 problem.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a Krylov subspace method that relies on repeated applications of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operator [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:linv-system"

\end_inset

] to solve the linear problem.
 Because only the matrix and not its inverse is used, the cost of the decomposit
ion in a direct solve is allayed and only the application of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 matrix is needed, not the explicit matrix.
 This solver can be used without a preconditioner for problems that are
 well-conditioned.
 For most problems, a preconditioner improves the performance significantly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Preconditioners
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:preconditioners"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To improve the conditioning of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 solution, a preconditioner can be added to the problem.
 A preconditioner is an approximation to the inverse of the original linear
 system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying this preconditioner 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 to both sides of the original linear equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:linv-system"

\end_inset

] results in a left-preconditioned system,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}^{-1}\mathcal{L}\alpha=\mathcal{P}^{-1}q.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a good choice of preconditioner, the combined matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^{-1}\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 (which need not be explicitly formed) has a lower condition number than
 the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

.
 The simplest preconditioner is the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which solves the system exactly in one iteration but provides no speedup
 compared to using a direct solver.
 A right-preconditioned system has a similar form,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\mathcal{P}^{-1}\mathcal{P}\alpha=q.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These preconditioners are applied here using the ILUT (incomplete LU decompositi
on with threshold) preconditioner from the Ifpack package of Trilinos.
 Instead of storing the entire LU decomposition of the preconditioner 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

, which is much less sparse than the original matrix, the ILUT decomposition
 instead stores an approximate form of the LU decomposition.
 The ILUT preconditioner allows specification of the level of fill and the
 drop tolerance of this approximate decomposition.
 The level of fill controls to the number of elements kept in the decomposition
 with respect to the original matrix.
 For a level of fill of 1.0, for instance, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 matrix has approximately the same number of elements as the original 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 The dropping technique of the ILUT preconditioner ensures that the remaining
 elements of the approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 matrix are larger than the drop tolerance.
 For most of the calculations in Chapters 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:method-of-manufactured"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:steady-results"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:eigenvalue-results"

\end_inset

, the level of fill is 1.0 and the drop tolerance is 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-12}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To precondition the streaming operator, a suitable preconditioner 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 must be defined.
 The most obvious option for a preconditioner is to use the streaming operator
 matrix itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{\mathcal{L=\mathcal{P}}}$
\end_inset

, and then let the ILUT preconditioner form an approximate inverse.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operation for the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 transport equations actually represents the application of linearly independent
 matrices for each group and direction, which can be denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

.
 The ILUT preconditioner stores a separate ILUT approximation for these
 preconditioners 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{n,g}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for each direction 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and group 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 This is the preconditioner used for most of the results in the following
 chapters, but this method does have major drawbacks in memory cost.
 These preconditioners can be formed anew for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 application, but this requires an excessive amount of computation that
 overshadows the benefits of the preconditioner.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second preconditioner implemented in the code relies on the assumption
 that a solution for the angular flux values at the centers of the weight
 functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n,g}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

, would be better-conditioned than a solution for the coefficients of the
 basis function expansion 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i,n,g}$
\end_inset

.
 The angular flux at the weight function centers 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is calculated from the basis function expansion as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}\alpha=\psi,\label{eq:basis-preconditioner-values}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{B}_{i,j,n,g}=b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Solving Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:basis-preconditioner-values"

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and inserting this expansion into the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 linear system from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:linv-system"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\mathcal{B}^{-1}\psi=q,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

results in an equation that solves for the angular flux at the weight function
 centers.
 To convert back to a solution for the angular flux expansion coefficients,
 the definition from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:basis-preconditioner-values"

\end_inset

 is again applied to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\mathcal{B}^{-1}\mathcal{B}\alpha=q,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is a right-preconditioned system for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operator with the preconditioner 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Unlike the first preconditioner, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is independent of both energy group and direction.
 The storage cost is therefore negligible, which reduces the memory requirements
 of solving the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 transport equations compared to the first preconditioner by one to two
 orders of magnitude.
 However, because this preconditioner is not as good of an approximation
 to the original 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 matrices, the number of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 iterations required to converge the solution can increase significantly.
 If the problem is solvable using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
