\begin_layout Subsection
Iteration on the scattering and fission sources
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:outer-iterations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The streaming problem in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:transport-sweep-operator"

\end_inset

 represents the solution for the angular flux for a given fixed neutron
 source.
 To solve the full transport equation, an additional solution step is required
 in iterating over the scattering and fission sources.
 The steady-state and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-eigenvalue cases are considered separately.
 For simplicity in notation, the Petrov-Galerkin superscripts from Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:operator-petrov"

\end_inset

 are dropped.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Steady-state outer iterations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a problem with no scattering or fission, the steady-state transport
 equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:operator-steady-petrov"

\end_inset

] becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta=\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}q\label{eq:purely-absorbing-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and a single application of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 operator produces the solution.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:purely-absorbing-operator"

\end_inset

 represents the first-flight source, or the source neutrons that have not
 interacted with the material.
 If there are reflective boundaries in the problem, a simple source iteration
 scheme is used to converge on the first-flight source, which includes neutrons
 that have been reflected but have not interacted with the material.
 After the neutrons have interacted with the material, they may scatter
 or produce fission neutrons.
 The neutrons from these subsequent generations are added to the first-flight
 source to calculate the full solution to the neutron transport equation.
 The iterations over the scattering and fission sources, referred to as
 the outer iterations, can be done directly through source (or Richardson)
 iteration,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta^{\ell+1}=\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\left(\mathcal{S}+\mathcal{F}\right)\beta^{\ell}+\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}q,\label{eq:source-iteration}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 refers to the iteration.
 This iteration process is continued until the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 converges to a chosen tolerance.
 The source iteration equation updates the scattering and fission sources
 for each subsequent generation of neutrons.
 If the initial guess for the solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{1}=\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}q$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 represents the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell^{th}$
\end_inset

 flight neutrons.
 For problems with high scattering ratios where the neutrons may scatter
 hundreds of times before leaving the problem through absorption or leakage,
 source iteration is not ideal as it requires an iteration to simulate each
 generation of neutrons.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Krylov solvers discussed in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:transport-sweep-operator"

\end_inset

 provide a simple way to speed up the calculations.
 Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:source-iteration"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten into the form used throughout Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:transport-discretization"

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{I}-\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\left(\mathcal{S}+\mathcal{F}\right)\right]\beta=\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}q,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and solved by applying a 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 solver to invert the combined operator on the lefthand side of the equation.
 The combined operator does not need to be formed explicitly, as 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 only requires the action of the operator.
 For the solution of this system, the code uses AztecOO, which is another
 Trilinos package, without preconditioning.
 Preconditioners such as diffusion synthetic acceleration 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "alcouffe-diffusion-1977"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 have been successfully applied to speed up convergence of the scattering
 and fission sources for various other transport discretizations, but are
 not investigated here for the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Eigenvalue outer iterations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The standard operator form of the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-eigenvalue equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:k-eigenvalue"

\end_inset

] for the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\beta=\mathcal{M}\left(\mathcal{S}+\frac{1}{k}\mathcal{F}\right)\mathcal{D}\beta,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where again the operators convert from the coefficients to the physical
 neutron flux where appropriate.
 One method of solving this equation is fixed point iteration, which updates
 the coefficients using a similar process to source iteration,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta^{\ell+1}=\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\left(\mathcal{S}+\frac{1}{k^{\ell}}\mathcal{F}\right)\beta^{\ell}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

After each iteration, the eigenvalue is updated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k^{\ell+1}=\frac{\left\Vert \mathcal{F}\beta^{\ell+1}\right\Vert }{\left\Vert \frac{1}{k}\mathcal{F}\phi^{\ell}-\mathcal{S}\left(\beta^{\ell+1}-\beta^{\ell}\right)\right\Vert },
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \left(\cdot\right)\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 represents a volume summation or integral 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "calef-nonlinear-2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Power iteration, which is more costly per iteration than fixed point iteration
 but also more stable, is written as
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta^{\ell+1}=\left(\mathcal{I}-\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}\right)^{-1}\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\frac{1}{k}\mathcal{F}\beta^{\ell},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while the update of the eigenvalue takes the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k^{\ell+1}=\frac{\left\Vert \mathcal{F}\beta^{\ell+1}\right\Vert }{\left\Vert \frac{1}{k^{\ell}}\mathcal{F}\beta^{\ell}\right\Vert }.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathcal{I}-\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 term in the power iteration represents the solution of a steady-state transport
 problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathcal{I}-\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}\right)\beta=s,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the given source.
 Thus, each power iteration requires a full steady-state solution when using
 power iteration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to the steady-state equation, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-eigenvalue problem can be solved more efficiently by using Krylov iterative
 methods.
 For a Krylov solver that requires isolation of the eigenvalue (such as
 Block Krylov-Schur), the Krylov iteration can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathcal{I}-\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}\right)^{-1}\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{F}\beta=k\beta,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where again a full steady-state problem must be solved for each eigenvalue
 iteration.
 Generalized eigensolvers reduce the cost further by supporting an operator
 on the eigenvalue side of the equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{F}\beta=k\left(\mathcal{I}-\mathcal{D}\mathcal{L}^{-1}\mathcal{M}\mathcal{S}\right)\beta.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This form of the eigenvalue equation is solved here with unpreconditioned
 Generalized Davidson using Anasazi, another Trilinos package.
 This significantly reduces computational cost compared to the other eigensolver
s 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hamilton-numerical-2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parallelization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:parallelization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The code for the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equations uses OpenMP 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dagum-openmp-1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 to implement thread-level parallelization.
 For the meshless integration technique (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:meshless-integration"

\end_inset

) the independence of the integrals for each weight function allows for
 parallel integration.
 For the background integration technique (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:background-mesh-integration"

\end_inset

), the integration is parallelized for the background cells and surfaces.
 As the basis and weight functions are not exclusive to a single background
 cell, each thread receives its own copy of the integrals.
 After the integration is complete for all threads, these integrals are
 summed together, which produces the full integral of each basis and weight
 function over the entire problem domain.
 Due to the adaptive integration technique introduced in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:background-mesh-integration"

\end_inset

, the time required to integrate the basis and weight functions over each
 cell is not constant.
 As such, the scheduling of the parallel integration is dynamic.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The operators such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 are parallelized for the spatial index.
 For instance, the weighted fission sources for the weight functions 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 are calculated in parallel.
 Because of the shared-memory model, the overlap of the basis function coefficie
nts between the various weighted fission sources is not an issue.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If directionally-dependent preconditioners (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:preconditioners"

\end_inset

) are used, their 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{ilut}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 decomposition is computed in parallel.
 If the preconditioners are independent of direction, each thread computes
 and uses a separate copy of the preconditioner.
 The streaming and collision operator is independent for each group and
 direction and is parallelized in direction.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{gmres}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 operator that performs the outer iterations does not occupy a large percentage
 of the computational time and is not parallelized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For extension to a higher number of processors than one node, the Trilinos
 linear algebra packages used for the outer and inner transport iterations
 support fully parallel computations using MPI.
 The weighting of the solution coefficients to calculate the scattering
 and fission sources and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 operator are the two places where the code requires communication between
 different spatial points, and these could be parallelized using MPI for
 the communication and Trilinos for the parallel linear solution of the
 equations.
 
\end_layout

