\begin_layout Standard
For the Kobayashi problem, the memory required to perform the simulation
 with preconditioning is around 75 GB, most of which is the storage of the
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{ilut}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 preconditioners.
 This memory cost scales approximately linearly with the product of the
 number of angles, groups and points.
 The memory cost of the simulation without preconditioning is around 7 GB,
 much of which is the storage of the integrated cross sections.
 For the basis function cross section weighting, the memory usage decreases
 to around 4 GB.
 The memory cost scales linearly with the product of the number of groups
 and points.
 An empirical equation for the memory in GB for the two solution techniques
 applied to the Kobayashi problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
M_{\text{no prec}} & \approx\begin{cases}
6.3\times10^{-5}J, & \text{basis weighting},\\
1.1\times10^{-4}J, & \text{full weighting},
\end{cases}\\
M_{\text{prec}} & \approx M_{\text{no prec}}+2.1\times10^{-6}JN,
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is the number of spatial points and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of directions.
 The scaling of the preconditioned method with the number of directions
 makes simultaneous angular and spatial convergence difficult to achieve,
 but the solution without preconditioning does not converge for many problems,
 including the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{vera}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 problem mentioned earlier in this section.
 
