reference "eq:sigma_f-full"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:sigma_t-basis"

\end_inset

] is performed using one of two methods, a meshless integration technique
 (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:meshless-integration"

\end_inset

) or a background mesh (Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:background-mesh-integration"

\end_inset

).
 The domain of integration for the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 discretization is defined by the region of support of the basis and weight
 functions.
 For the functions described in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:meshless-functions"

\end_inset

, the support region of each basis or weight function is a circle in 2D
 or a sphere in 3D.
 The region of support for the intersection of a basis and weight function
 is often a 2D or 3D lens.
 These geometries are complicated somewhat by the addition of boundaries,
 which limit the region of support to the physical problem domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An integral over the region 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be performed numerically as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{R}f\left(\bm{x}\right)dV=\sum_{i}c_{i}f\left(\bm{x}_{i}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the integration weights and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the integration ordinates.
 One method of calculating the integration ordinates and weights is by using
 a tensor product quadrature.
 Starting with two integration quadratures for the integrals over 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (with the ordinates and weights 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}^{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}^{y}$
\end_inset

), the tensor-product quadrature over a 2D Cartesian region with the limits
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R_{y}$
\end_inset

 can be written as
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{R_{y}}\int_{R_{x}}f\left(\bm{x}\right)dxdy=\sum_{i,j}c_{i,j}f\left(\bm{x}_{i,j}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bm{x}_{i,j}=\left(x_{i},y_{j}\right),\\
c_{i,j}=c_{i}^{x}c_{j}^{y}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Integrals for the geometries described in Secs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:meshless-integration"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:background-mesh-integration"

\end_inset

