\begin_layout Subsubsection
Cartesian regions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integration quadratures such as the Gauss-Legendre quadrature used here
 are often given over the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate the integration ordinates, the geometry is mapped onto simple
 Cartesian regions.
 In one dimension, to convert from 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

, the mapping
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x\left(\xi\right)=\frac{1-\xi}{2}x_{1}+\frac{1+\xi}{2}x_{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is applied.
 The differential length for the mapping is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dx=\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}d\xi.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

After the change of variables, a one-dimensional integral over the Cartesian
 region 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:cartesian-2d-integral"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}}f\left(x\right)dx & =\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}\int_{-1}^{1}f\left(x\left(\xi\right)\right)d\xi\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}\sum_{i}c_{i}f\left(x\left(\xi_{i}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i}C_{i}f\left(X_{i}\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the original integration ordinates in 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the original integration weights.
 The modified integration ordinates and weights are then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
X_{i}=x\left(\xi_{i}\right),\\
C_{i}=\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}c_{i}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a Cartesian region in 2D, the conversion from 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left[x_{1},x_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\left[y_{1},y_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 follows the same process, using the mappings
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
x\left(\xi\right)=\frac{1-\xi}{2}x_{1}+\frac{1+\xi}{2}x_{2},\\
y\left(\eta\right)=\frac{1-\eta}{2}y_{1}+\frac{1-\eta}{2}y_{2}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset

The differentials are independent due to the orthogonality of the coordinate
 system,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
dx=\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}d\xi,\\
dy=\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2}d\eta,
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

and a two-dimensional integral over this region becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\int_{x_{1}}^{x_{2}}\int_{y_{1}}^{y_{2}}f\left(x,y\right)dxdy & =\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2}\int_{-1}^{1}\int_{-1}^{1}f\left(x\left(\xi\right),y\left(\eta\right)\right)d\xi d\eta\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{x_{2}-x_{1}}{2}\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{2}\sum_{i,j}c_{i}^{x}c_{j}^{x}f\left(x\left(\xi_{i}\right),y\left(\eta_{j}\right)\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

The modified integration ordinates and weights can be calculated similarly
 to those in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cartesian-2d-integral"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

