 The coordinate system is rotated so both radii are located at the same
 point on the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 axis and then translated so that one of the circles is located at the origin.
 In this coordinate system, all integrals appear similar to the one pictured
 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:lens-integration-region"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This transformation from the Cartesian coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 to simplified coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x},\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bar{x}\\
\bar{y}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}\\
y_{1}
\end{array}\right]+\frac{1}{d}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\Delta x & -\Delta y\\
\Delta y & \Delta x
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
x\\
y
\end{array}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the distances
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\Delta x=x_{2}-x_{1},\\
\Delta y=y_{2}-y_{1},\\
d=\sqrt{\Delta x^{2}+\Delta y^{2}}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this coordinate system, the equations for each circular support region
 can be written
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bar{x}^{2}+\bar{y}^{2}=r_{1}^{2},\\
\left(\bar{x}-d\right)^{2}+\bar{y}^{2}=r_{2}^{2},
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where the radii of the circles (which remain unchanged in this coordinate
 system) are 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The two intercepts of these circles are located at the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{x}_{int},\ \bar{y}_{int}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{x}_{int},\ -\bar{y}_{int}\right)$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bar{x}_{int}=\frac{d^{2}+r_{1}^{2}-r_{2}^{2}}{2d},\\
\bar{y}_{int}=\frac{\sqrt{2d^{2}\left(r_{1}^{2}+r_{2}^{2}\right)-\left(r_{1}^{2}-r_{2}^{2}\right)^{2}-d^{4}}}{2d}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The integration limits in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 dimension are variable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bar{x}_{min}\left(\bar{y}\right)=d-\sqrt{r_{2}^{2}-\bar{y}^{2}},\\
\bar{x}_{max}\left(\bar{y}\right)=\sqrt{r_{1}^{2}-\bar{y}^{2}},
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

while the integration limits in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 dimension go from 
\begin_inset Formula $-\bar{y}_{int}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}_{int}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conversion of the integral from Cartesian to simplified coordinates
 has a Jacobian determinant of one,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{\left(x,y\right)\to\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)}=\left|\begin{array}{cc}
\dfrac{dx}{d\bar{x}} & \dfrac{dx}{d\bar{x}}\\
\dfrac{dy}{d\bar{x}} & \dfrac{dy}{d\bar{y}}
\end{array}\right|=1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which means the integral can be transformed to the simplified coordinates
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V}f\left(x,y\right)dV=\int_{-\bar{y}_{int}}^{\bar{y}_{int}}\int_{\bar{x}_{min}\left(\bar{y}\right)}^{\bar{x}_{max}\left(\bar{y}\right)}f\left(x\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right),y\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\right)d\bar{x}d\bar{y}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This integral is transformed a second time from the simplified coordinate
 system into a standard coordinate system 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi\in\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in\left[-1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bar{x}=\frac{\bar{x}_{max}\left(\bar{y}\left(\eta\right)\right)-\bar{x}_{min}\left(\bar{y}\left(\eta\right)\right)}{2}\xi+\frac{\bar{x}_{max}\left(\bar{y}\left(\eta\right)\right)+\bar{x}_{min}\left(\bar{y}\left(\eta\right)\right)}{2},\\
\bar{y}=\bar{y}_{int}\eta.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Unlike the first transformation, the Jacobian determinant for this transformatio
n is not equal to a constant,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\to\left(\xi,\eta\right)}=\left|\begin{array}{cc}
\dfrac{d\bar{x}}{d\xi} & \dfrac{d\bar{x}}{d\eta}\\
\dfrac{d\bar{y}}{d\xi} & \dfrac{d\bar{y}}{d\eta}
\end{array}\right|=\left(\frac{\bar{x}_{max}\left(\bar{y}\right)-\bar{x}_{min}\left(\bar{y}\right)}{2}\right)\bar{y}_{int}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This Jacobian is used to map the integral to the local coordinates,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{V}f\left(x,y\right)dV=\int_{-1}^{1}\int_{-1}^{1}f\left(x\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right),y\left(\bar{x},\bar{y}\right)\right)\left(\frac{\bar{x}_{max}\left(\bar{y}\right)-\bar{x}_{min}\left(\bar{y}\right)}{2}\right)\bar{y}_{int}d\xi d\eta.\label{eq:lens-integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For simplicity, the dependencies of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 have been suppressed.
 The conversion of this continuous integral to a numerical quadrature follows
 the same procedure as in past sections.
 
\end_layout

