\begin_layout Standard
The process of verification by the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mms}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 begins with a manufactured solution to the equation, which for the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equations derived in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:transport-discretization"

\end_inset

 is the moments of the angular flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell,g}^{m}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The manufactured solution, which is denoted here by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\ell,g}^{m}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, is inserted into the original equation to analytically calculate the moments
 of the internal source, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\ell,g}^{m}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

, and the boundary source, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{n,g}^{inc}\left(\bm{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 A simulation is performed using these sources to calculate a numerical
 solution to the problem.
 If the code is working correctly, the numerical solution matches the manufactur
ed solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To calculate the expected internal source for the transport equation, the
 internal source is expanded using spherical harmonics [as in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:source-expansion"

\end_inset

].
 The spherical harmonics moments are orthogonal, meaning that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{4\pi}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}\right)Y_{\ell'}^{m'}\left(\bm{\Omega}\right)d\Omega=\frac{4\pi}{2\ell+1}\delta_{\ell,\ell'}\delta_{m,m'},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{a,b}$
\end_inset

 is the Kronecker delta function from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:delta-function"

\end_inset

.
 For example, multiplying the internal source term in the transport equation
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\ell'}^{m'}$
\end_inset

 and integrating over the unit sphere results in the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{4\pi}Y_{\ell'}^{m'}\left[\sum_{\ell=0}^{L}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell}^{m}Q_{\ell,g}^{m}\right]d\Omega=\begin{cases}
Q_{\ell,g}, & \ell'=\ell'\text{ and }m'=m',\\
0, & \text{otherwise},
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which isolates the moments of the internal source.
 To calculate the manufactured internal source, the manufactured flux is
 inserted into the multigroup transport equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:multigroup"

\end_inset

] with the steady-state approximation.
 This equation with the known manufactured solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\ell'}^{m'}$
\end_inset

 and integrated over all directions.
 Using the orthogonality property, the resulting transport equation can
 be solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\ell,g}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q_{\ell,g}^{m} & =\int_{4\pi}Y_{\ell}^{m}\Biggl[\bm{\Omega}\cdot\bm{\nabla}\Psi_{g}+\Sigma_{t;g}\Psi_{g}\nonumber \\
 & \qquad\qquad\qquad\left.-\sum_{\ell'=0}^{\infty}\frac{2\ell'+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m'=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell'}^{m'}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\Sigma_{s;\ell',g'\to g}\Phi_{\ell',g'}^{m'}-\frac{\chi_{g}}{4\pi}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\nu_{g'}\Sigma_{f;g'}\Phi_{0,g'}^{0}d\Omega\right].
\end{align}

\end_inset

Replacing the manufactured angular flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{g}$
\end_inset

 by a spherical harmonics expansion in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and using orthogonality to perform the integration for the scattering and
 fission terms, the equation simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
Q_{\ell,g} & =\sum_{\ell'=0}^{\infty}\sum_{m'=-\ell}^{\ell}\left(\frac{2\ell'+1}{4\pi}\int_{4\pi}\bm{\Omega}Y_{\ell}^{m}Y_{\ell'}^{m'}d\Omega\right)\cdot\bm{\nabla}\Phi_{\ell',g}^{m'}+\Sigma_{t;g}\Phi_{\ell,g}^{m}\nonumber \\
 & \qquad-\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\Sigma_{s;\ell,g'\to g}\Phi_{\ell,g'}^{m}-\delta_{\ell,0}\chi_{g}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\nu_{g'}\Sigma_{f;g'\to g}\Phi_{\ell,g'}^{m}.\label{eq:manufactured-internal}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Due to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 term inside the remaining angular integral, if the manufactured solution
 has spherical harmonics moments of maximum degree 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, the calculated source 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

 has nonzero values of one spherical harmonic degree higher, or 
\begin_inset Formula $L+1$
\end_inset

.
 This integral, which is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{2\ell'+1}{4\pi}\int_{4\pi}Y_{1}^{m''}Y_{\ell'}^{m'}Y_{\ell}^{m}d\Omega
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $m''=-1,0,1$
\end_inset

, can be performed analytically using Clebsch-Gordon coefficients.
 For simplicity, this integral is performed numerically for the problems
 in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:manufactured-problems"

\end_inset

 using a Gauss-Legendre quadrature with 256 ordinates in 1D or an 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{ldfe}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 quadrature with 16384 or 32768 ordinates in 2D or 3D, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The boundary source for the manufactured equations is set to the value of
 the desired source, or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{n,g}^{inc}=\sum_{\ell=0}^{L}\frac{2\ell+1}{4\pi}\sum_{m=-\ell}^{\ell}Y_{\ell}^{m}\left(\bm{\Omega}_{n}\right)\Phi_{\ell,g}^{m},\label{eq:manufactured-boundary}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

