\begin_layout Standard
The two manufactured problems considered here are a problem with piecewise
 constant cross sections and a problem with continuous, sinusoidal cross
 sections.
 The manufactured solutions and cross sections are defined in three dimensions.
 For two dimensions, the solutions and cross sections are evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 For both problems, the basis and weight function centers are placed on
 the nodes of an equally-spaced Cartesian grid with an equal number of points
 in each dimension, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{x}=N_{y}=N_{z}$
\end_inset

.
 The problems use 256 and 512 angular quadrature ordinates in 2D and 3D,
 respectively.
 The number of points, the number of neighbors in the radius calculation,
 the Wendland function [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:wendland"

\end_inset

] and the value of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{supg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 are all varied to find optimal values that converge appropriately and retain
 good conditioning for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 operation.
 For each permutation of parameters, the flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is calculated and compared to the initial manufactured flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{\ell,g}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 The relative 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}$
\end_inset

 integral error over the entire problem domain 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(L_{1}\text{ integral error}\right)_{g}=\frac{\int_{V}\left|\phi_{0,g}^{0}-\Phi_{0,g}^{0}\right|dV}{\int_{V}\Phi_{0,g}^{0}dV},\label{eq:l1-error-manufactured}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is then calculated numerically using a Gauss-Legendre outer product quadrature
 to measure convergence and compare between parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first problem, which has two energy groups and a domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $-0.01\leq x,y,z\leq0.01$
\end_inset

, uses the cross sections in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:vera1e-xs"

\end_inset

 from the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{vera}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1E problem as described in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:vera"

\end_inset

.
 The cross sections are piecewise constant and depend only on the distance
 from the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\left\Vert \bm{x}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

, making the cross sections cylindrically symmetric in two dimensions and
 spherically symmetric in three dimensions.
 The three cross sections used include the fuel cross sections from 
\begin_inset Formula $0.0\leq r\leq0.0045$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{ifba}
\end_layout

\end_inset

