\begin_layout Standard
This slab-geometry problem is designed to test the ability of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 discretization to calculate solutions in optically thick and optically
 thin problems.
 The problem consists of a homogeneous, one-group, purely-absorbing slab
 with a length of 
\begin_inset Formula $L=1.0$
\end_inset

, an isotropic source of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{0}$
\end_inset

 on the left side of the problem and no internal source.
 The transport equation for this problem with the appropriate boundary condition
s can be written as
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\mu\frac{\partial}{\partial x}\psi\left(x,\mu\right)+\Sigma_{t}\psi\left(x,\mu\right)=0,\qquad0\leq x\leq L,\quad-1\leq\mu\leq1,\\
\psi\left(x,\mu\right)\bigg|_{x=0}=\psi_{0},\qquad\mu>0,\\
\psi\left(x,\mu\right)\bigg|_{x=L}=0,\qquad\mu<0,
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the angle cosine.
 The solution to this problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{\text{exact}}\left(x,\mu\right)=\begin{cases}
\psi_{0}\exp\left(-\dfrac{\Sigma_{t}x}{\mu}\right), & \mu>0,\\
0, & \mu<0,
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

from which the scalar flux at any point in the problem can be calculated
 by integrating over the angular cosine,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\phi_{\text{exact}}\left(x\right) & =\int_{-1}^{1}\psi\left(x,\mu\right)d\mu\nonumber \\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{0}\exp\left(-\frac{\Sigma_{t}x}{\mu}\right)d\mu.\label{eq:slab-scalar-flux}
\end{align}

\end_inset

This solution provides results to compare against for the numerical simulations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The angular distribution of neutrons that reach the right edge of the slab
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset

 is forward peaked for an optically thick problem (
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{t}\gg1$
\end_inset

), whereas for an optically thin problem (
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{t}\ll1$
\end_inset

), the angular distribution of neutrons is relatively flat except near 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\ll1$
\end_inset

, for which the probability of a neutron reaching the far side of the slab
 is very low.
 These distributions are shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:slab-angular distribution"

\end_inset

 for various total cross section values.
 The angular integration of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{t}=1.0$
\end_inset

 case is straightforward and does not require a large number of ordinates
 due to the approximately linear shape of the function.
 The cases of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{t}=0.01$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{t}=100$
\end_inset

, however, have large gradients that require many ordinates to accurately
 integrate.
 Because of this, 8192 angular ordinates are used for this problem, as shown
