\begin_layout Subsection
Heat conduction equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heat conduction equation is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\rho c_{p}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}-\bm{\nabla}\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)=\dot{q},\label{eq:heat-transfer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the specific heat at constant pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the mass density, 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the thermal conductivity and 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}$
\end_inset

 is the volumetric heat generation rate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bergman-fundamentals-2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 Each of the three terms in the equation has units of energy per time (e.g.
 watts per second).
 The time derivative term implies that the change in the temperature due
 to a change in energy is proportional to the density and specific heat
 of the material.
 The diffusion term states that the energy change due to convection for
 a certain region of the problem depends on the energy flow into and out
 of that region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The convective boundary condition depends on the difference in the material
 temperature at the surface, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and the fluid temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\infty}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k\bm{n}\cdot\bm{\nabla}T=h\left[T_{\infty}-T\right],\label{eq:convective-boundary}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{n}$
\end_inset

 is the surface normal for the boundary surface.
 This equation describes the net direction of energy transfer for a convective
 boundary, from the hotter to the colder material.
 The convective boundary condition can be either an energy source to the
 system when 
\begin_inset Formula $T>T_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 or a sink when 
\begin_inset Formula $T<T_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 For a reflective boundary condition (i.e.
 no heat transfer in or out of a surface), the convection coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 can be set to zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steady-state equation assumes that the temperature does not depend on
 time, which simplifies Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:heat-transfer"

\end_inset

 to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\bm{\nabla}\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)=\dot{q}.\label{eq:steady-heat-transfer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Taken together with the boundary condition in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:convective-boundary"

\end_inset

, this steady-state equation states that the energy sources and sinks are
 balanced.
 Specifically, the energy flow out of any region in the problem equals the
 energy flow into and the generation rate inside of that region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Heat equation discretization
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:heat-equation-discretization"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The heat equation is discretized using the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{mlpg}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 method, similarly to the neutron transport equation in Secs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:weak-form-transport"

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:petrov-galerkin"

\end_inset

 but with identical basis and weight functions.
 As the convection equation is a diffusion instead of an advection equation,
 no stabilization is required to prevent oscillations in the solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive the weak form of the heat equations, the steady-state conduction
 equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:steady-heat-transfer"

\end_inset

] is multiplied by a series of test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}$
\end_inset

 and integrated over the support region for the test function, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{j}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\bm{\nabla}\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)dV=\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\dot{q}dV,\qquad j=1,\dots,J.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The conduction term is integrated by parts to separate the integral into
 surface and volume-integrated terms,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}\bm{n}\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)dS+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)dV=\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\dot{q}dV,\qquad j=1,\dots,J.\label{eq:heat-integrated-by-parts}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The integrand of the surface integral in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:heat-integrated-by-parts"

\end_inset

 contains the gradient term in the convective boundary condition [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:convective-boundary"

\end_inset

].
 This term inside the surface integral is replaced by the boundary condition,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
-\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}h\left[T_{\infty}-T\left(\bm{x}\right)\right]dS+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)dV=\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\dot{q}dV,\qquad j=1,\dots,J.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Separating the surface integral into the known and unknown portions gives
 the final weak form of the heat equation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}hTdS+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}T\right)dV=\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\dot{q}dV+\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}hT_{\infty}dS,\qquad j=1,\dots,J.\label{eq:weak-heat-transfer}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of the terms containing the unknown temperature distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 are on the right side of the equation.
 To solve for the temperature, a basis function expansion 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T\left(\bm{x}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{J}\zeta_{i}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the expansion coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{i}$
\end_inset

 and basis functions 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 is inserted into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-heat-transfer"

\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i}\left[\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}hb_{i}dS+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}b_{i}\right)dV\right]\zeta_{i}=\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\dot{q}dV+\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}hT_{\infty}dS,\qquad j=1,\dots,J.\label{eq:galerkin-heat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:galerkin-heat"

\end_inset

 represents a linear system of equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{A}\bm{\zeta}=\bm{s}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 with the matrix and source vector of
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:matrix-galerkin-heat"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
A_{i,j}=\int_{S_{j}}hw_{j}b_{i}dS+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\bm{\nabla}w_{j}\right)\cdot\left(k\bm{\nabla}b_{i}\right)dV,\\
s_{j}=\int_{V_{j}}w_{j}\dot{q}dV+\int_{S_{j}}w_{j}hT_{\infty}dS.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Unlike the transport equation, this equation contains no unknowns in the
 source term.
 Because of this, only a single linear solve is required to solve the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For cylindrical geometry without axial or longitudinal dependence, the boundary
 condition at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

 is reflective,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial T}{\partial r}=0\bigg|_{r=0},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the heat transfer equation simplifies to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[rw_{j}hT\right]_{r=R}+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\frac{\partial w_{j}}{\partial r}\right)\left(k\frac{\partial T}{\partial r}\right)rdr=\int_{V_{j}}rw_{j}\dot{q}dr+\left[rw_{j}hT_{\infty}\right]_{r=R},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the outer radius of the cylinder.
 The linear system from Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:matrix-galerkin-heat"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:matrix-galerkin-heat-cylindrical"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
A_{i,j}=\left[rw_{j}hb_{i}\right]_{r=R}+\int_{V_{j}}\left(\frac{\partial w_{j}}{\partial r}\right)\left(k\frac{\partial b_{i}}{\partial r}\right)rdr,\\
s_{j}=\int_{V_{j}}rw_{j}\dot{q}dr+\left[rw_{j}hT_{\infty}\right]_{r=R}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

