\begin_layout Standard
Heat conduction and neutron transport are strongly linked in nuclear reactors.
 The fission of the nuclear fuel acts as an energy source that affects the
 temperature of the fuel.
 The heat from the fuel is transferred through through the gap and cladding
 of the fuel pin, after which convection by the water moves the heat away
 from the fuel pin.
 In the reverse direction, the temperature of the fuel, gap and cladding
 affects the cross sections for neutron transport as a result of Doppler
 broadening.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:vera-heat-problem"

\end_inset

, the two-way coupling presented in this section is applied to a realistic
 pincell problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Temperature dependence of the cross section
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The macroscopic cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 is related to the microscopic cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma\equiv\sigma N,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number density of the nuclei in the material.
 The dependence of the number density on temperature as result of thermal
 expansion is neglected in this section, which instead concerns the microscopic
 cross section changes in the laboratory frame as a result of Doppler broadening.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The microscopic cross sections depend on the relative velocity between the
 neutrons and the target nuclei.
 Doppler broadening of the cross sections is necessary because the neutron
 transport equation is solved in the laboratory frame of reference, not
 in the frame of reference of the nuclei.
 The nuclei move with respect to the laboratory frame due to the kinetic
 energy of the atoms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cacuci-handbook-2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The exact treatment of Doppler broadening by Cullen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cullen-exact-1976"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 calculates a microscopic cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(v,T\right)$
\end_inset

 for a given temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and laboratory-frame neutron velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 from base cross section data 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(v_{r},T_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 for a different temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

 and the relative neutron velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This exact treatment does not apply directly to the energy-integrated multigroup
 cross sections, given that the neutron velocity has already been integrated
 out of the cross section dependencies and the cross sections are assumed
 to already be in the laboratory frame.
 To approximate Doppler broadening, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Combined Doppler broadening model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yesilyurt-fly-2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 assumes an expansion of the microscopic cross sections in terms of temperature,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma\left(T\right)=\sum_{i=0}^{\infty}\left[a_{i}T^{-i/2}+b_{i}T^{i/2}+c_{i}T^{i}\right],\label{eq:cross-section-temperature-expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are expansion coefficients.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 term represents cross section physics that are positively correlated with
 material temperature, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 term represents the opposite correlation.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 term represents physics that are not monotonic with respect to temperature.
 To truncate the expansion, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 coefficients are assumed to be nonzero for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,6$
\end_inset

 and y the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}$
\end_inset

 coefficients are assumed to have only a single term for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the problems in this section, two cross sections 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(T_{0}\right)=\sigma_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(T_{1}\right)=\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 are assumed to be known at temperatures below (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}$
\end_inset

) and above (
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

) those expected in the physical system.
 The temperature is calculated as an interpolation between these two cross
 sections with a functional dependence based on Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cross-section-temperature-expansion"

\end_inset

.
 As the cross section interpolation for two points requires only two unknowns
 and should be monotonic, the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 terms are neglected and the expansion is further truncated to include only
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 term and the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 term, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma\left(T\right)=c_{0}+a_{1}\sqrt{\frac{1}{T}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To solve for the expansion coefficients, the constraints from the known
 cross sections are applied to get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma\left(T\right)=\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{T_{0}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{T_{1}}}\right)^{-1}\left[\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{T}}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{T_{1}}}\right)\sigma_{0}+\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{T_{0}}}-\sqrt{\frac{1}{T}}\right)\sigma_{1}\right].\label{eq:cross-section-temperature-approximation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This is the function used to interpolate between two known values of the
 cross section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculating heat generation from the neutron flux
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a nuclear reactor, the volumetric heat generation rate in the heat conductio
n equation is fission.
 The three components of prompt fission energy release are the kinetic energy
 of the fission products, neutrons and photons.
 The fission products and photons, which unlike neutrons do not travel far
 from the fission site, make up over 97 percent of the prompt fission energy
 release for the isotopes of uranium and plutonium used in nuclear reactors
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "madland-total-2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The remainder of the fission energy (around 10 percent total) is emitted
 by the decay of fission products, as anti-neutrinos or by the capture of
 fission neutrons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "stacey-nuclear-2018"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 The following equations assume that all of the energy created in a fission
 event is deposited at the site of fission.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rate at which fission events occur in each energy group is calculated
 by multiplying the scalar flux 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{0,g}^{0}$
\end_inset

 [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:multigroup"

\end_inset

] by the fission cross section 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{f;g}$
\end_inset

.
 To calculate the total energy source from fission, this rate is multiplied
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{g}$
\end_inset

, the mean energy released in a fission event for energy group 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, and summed over all energy groups,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\dot{q}=\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\kappa_{g'}\Sigma_{f;g'}\phi_{0,g'}^{0},\label{eq:fission-energy-source}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In the discretized heat conduction equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:weak-heat-transfer"

\end_inset

], this energy generation rate is integrated over volume for each weighted
 equation.
 This requires spatially-dependent values of the cross sections and scalar
 flux, which can be calculated using an interpolation for the cross sections
 [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cross-section-temperature-approximation"

\end_inset

] and a basis expansion for the moments of the angular flux [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:moment-expansion"

\end_inset

].
\end_layout

