\begin_layout Standard
The dependence of the thermal conductivity on the temperature is usually
 calculated using empirical equations from experimental results 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bird-transport-2002"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
 For this problem, three empirical formulas are used for each of the fuel,
 gas and cladding.
 The formulas depend on temperature and return the thermal conductivity
 in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{W}/\text{m}\cdot\text{K}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{ifba}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 thermal conductivity is neglected due to its small volume.
 The thermal conductivity of the fuel is evaluated using an equation from
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{iaea}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 combined measurements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "agency-thermophysical-2006"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{fuel}=\frac{100}{7.5408+17.692t+3.6142t^{2}}+\frac{6400}{t^{5/2}}\exp\left(\frac{-16.35}{t}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $t=T/1000\text{ K}$
\end_inset

.
 The gap conductance is calculated using the URGAP model for helium from
 Lassmann and Hohlefeld 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "lassmann-revised-1987"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{gap}=a_{\lambda}T^{b_{\lambda}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\lambda}=0.17632\times10^{-2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\lambda}=0.77163$
\end_inset

.
 Finally, the cladding thermal conductivity is a correlation from the MATPRO
 library 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "cacuci-handbook-2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k_{clad}=7.51+2.09\times10^{-2}T-1.45\times10^{-5}T^{2}+7.69\times10^{-9}T^{3}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

These functions are evaluated for each quadrature point when performing
 the numerical integration of Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:matrix-galerkin-heat"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:matrix-galerkin-heat-cylindrical"

\end_inset

.
 The temperature dependence of these conductivities in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{W}/\text{cm}\cdot\text{K}$
\end_inset

