\begin_layout Standard
In the following sections, the following equations are provided for surfaces
 represented by a plane, cylinder, sphere and ellipsoid:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The normal vector of the surface at each point on the surface,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The distance to intersection and point of intersection of a particle incident
 on the surface, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The aspect of a particle with respect to the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aspect for each surface can be positive, negative or coincident.
 If the aspect is coincident, the particle is located on the surface.
 The equations are derived using vector notation for simplicity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Plane
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general equation for a plane which includes point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and has the normal vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{n}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\cdot\bm{n}=0.\label{eq:plane-csg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A particle located at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}$
\end_inset

 moving in direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{1}$
\end_inset

 has the trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{x}_{p}\left(s\right)=\bm{g}_{0}+\bm{g}_{1}s,\label{eq:csg-position}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the distance traveled from the initial point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 This equation is inserted into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:plane-csg"

\end_inset

 and solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 to get the distance to intersection for the particle,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{int}=\frac{\left(\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{g}_{0}\right)\cdot\bm{n}}{\bm{g}_{1}\cdot\bm{n}}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The point of intersection can be found by advancing the particle by distance
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{int}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:csg-position"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The geometric relationship between a particle at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}$
\end_inset

 and a plane is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{n}\cdot\left(\bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\begin{cases}
>0, & \text{positive},\\
<0, & \text{negative},\\
=0, & \text{coincident}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Similar equations are derived for each of the other shapes, with the addition
 of a calculation for the normal vector, which is a given in the plane equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cylinder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation for a cylinder with a centerline axis in direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 that runs through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{\Omega}\cdot\left(\bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\bm{\Omega}\right\Vert ^{2}=r^{2},\label{eq:cylinder-csg}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the radius of the cylinder and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \left(\cdot\right)\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 calculates the length of the vector.
 The particle position is defined the same as before according to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:csg-position"

\end_inset

.
 Inserting this equation into Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cylinder-csg"

\end_inset

, the cylindrical equation becomes (after some simplification) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \bm{k}_{0}+\bm{k}_{1}s\right\Vert ^{2}=r^{2},\label{eq:cylinder-csg-vec}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with the two constant vectors 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bm{k}_{0}=\left[\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0}-\bm{\Omega}\cdot\left(\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\bm{\Omega}\right],\\
\bm{k}_{1}=\left[\bm{g}_{1}-\left(\bm{\Omega}\cdot\bm{g}_{1}\right)\bm{\Omega}\right].
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{k}_{0}$
\end_inset

 represents the vector rejection of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Omega}$
\end_inset

, or the part of the vector connecting the midpoint of the cylinder to the
 position of the particle that is perpendicular to the cylinder axis.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{k}_{1}$
\end_inset

 has a similar geometric meaning for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{1}$
\end_inset

, the direction of the particle.
 The equation can further simplify to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
r^{2} & =\left(\bm{k}_{0}+\bm{k}_{1}s\right)\cdot\left(\bm{k}_{0}+\bm{k}_{1}s\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{0}+2\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{1}s+\bm{k}_{1}\cdot\bm{k}_{1}s^{2}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

Defining the constants
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\ell_{0}=\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{0}-r^{2},\label{eq:cylinder-l0}\\
\ell_{1}=\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{1},\\
\ell_{2}=\bm{k}_{1}\cdot\bm{k}_{1},
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

the solution to this equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{int}=\frac{-\ell_{1}\pm\sqrt{\ell_{1}^{2}-\ell_{0}\ell_{2}}}{\ell_{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the distance to collision of the particle with the cylinder.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, the particle continues along the axis of the cylinder without intersection.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}^{2}-\ell_{0}\ell_{2}<0,$
\end_inset

 there are no intersections between the particle and the surface.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aspect of a particle with respect to a cylinder can be found by setting
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{k}_{1}=\bm{0}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cylinder-csg-vec"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{0}=r^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and evaluating the sign of the equation for position 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}$
\end_inset

 [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:cylinder-l0"

\end_inset

],
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell_{0}\begin{cases}
>0, & \text{outside},\\
<0, & \text{inside},\\
=0, & \text{coincident}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Finally, the normal direction of a particle on a cylinder at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be found by normalizing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{k}_{0}$
\end_inset

 vector,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{n}=\frac{\bm{k}_{0}}{\left\Vert \bm{k}_{0}\right\Vert }.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation of a sphere is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}\right\Vert ^{2}=r^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Inserting the particle position from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:csg-position"

\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\Vert \bm{g}_{0}+\bm{g}_{1}s-\bm{x}_{0}\right\Vert ^{2}=r^{2},
\]

\end_inset

which can be simplified by defining 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bm{k}_{0}=\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0},\\
\bm{k}_{1}=\bm{g}_{1},
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \bm{k}_{0}+\bm{k}_{1}s\right\Vert ^{2}=r^{2}.\label{eq:sphere-csg-vec}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This form of the equation is identical to the cylindrical equations and
 the results from the cylindrical equations follow, but the spherical equations
 can be simplified by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{1}\cdot\bm{g}_{1}=1$
\end_inset

, which results in a distance to intersection of
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{int}=-\ell_{1}\pm\sqrt{\ell_{1}^{2}-\ell_{0}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\ell_{0}=\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{0}-r^{2},\\
\ell_{1}=\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{1}.
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}^{2}-\ell_{0}<0$
\end_inset

, there are no intersections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To check if a particle is inside of the sphere, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}$
\end_inset

 constant is used to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell_{0}\begin{cases}
>0, & \text{outside},\\
<0, & \text{inside},\\
=0, & \text{coincident},
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as for the cylindrical case.
 The normal direction of a point on the sphere at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{n}=\frac{\bm{k}_{0}}{\left\Vert \bm{k}_{0}\right\Vert }.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ellipsoid
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations for the ellipsoid are similar to the spherical and cylindrical
 equations.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{q}=\left\{ \frac{1}{a},\frac{1}{b},\frac{1}{c}\right\} ,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the equation for an ellipsoid with semiaxes 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 along the Cartesian axes is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \left(\bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\circ\bm{q}\right\Vert =1,
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 represents the entrywise product.
 The equation for a traveling particle is inserted into this equation, which
 results in 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \left(\bm{g}_{0}+\bm{g}_{1}s-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\circ\bm{q}\right\Vert =1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Letting
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\bm{k}_{0}=\left(\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\circ\bm{q},\\
\bm{k}_{1}=\bm{g}_{1}\circ\bm{q},
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

the equations become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \bm{k}_{0}+\bm{k}_{1}s\right\Vert =1.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The results from the equations for a cylinder with the same equation follow.
 The constants
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\ell_{0}=\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{0}-1,\\
\ell_{1}=\bm{k}_{0}\cdot\bm{k}_{1},\\
\ell_{2}=\bm{k}_{1}\cdot\bm{k}_{1},
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

simplify solution of the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s=\frac{-\ell_{1}\pm\sqrt{\ell_{1}^{2}-\ell_{0}\ell_{2}}}{\ell_{2}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as before.
 This is the distance to collision with the ellipsoid.
 As for the cylinder, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1}^{2}-\ell_{0}\ell_{2}<0$
\end_inset

 there are no intersections.
 The aspect of the particle with respect to the surface is also the same,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell_{0}\begin{cases}
>0, & \text{outside},\\
<0, & \text{inside},\\
=0, & \text{coincident}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the normal direction for a point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{g}_{0}$
\end_inset

 on the surface of the ellipsoid, the property that the gradient vector
 of surface is perpendicular to the surface is employed.
 The gradient has the magnitude
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bm{N} & =\nabla\left[\left\Vert \left(\bm{x}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\circ\bm{q}\right\Vert -1\right]\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\left(\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\circ\bm{q}\circ\bm{q}}{\left\Vert \left(\bm{g}_{0}-\bm{x}_{0}\right)\circ\bm{q}\right\Vert }\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\bm{k}_{0}\circ\bm{q}}{\left\Vert \bm{k}_{0}\right\Vert },
\end{align}

\end_inset

which when normalized is the normal direction of the surface,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{n}=\frac{\bm{N}}{\left\Vert \bm{N}\right\Vert }.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

