\begin_layout Section
Alternate discretization of the strong form of the transport equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:alternate-discretization-strong"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basis and weight functions for the strong-form transport equation in
 Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:strong-discretization"

\end_inset

 are either compact, which produces a sparse transport operator (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

), or global, which produces a dense transport operator.
 For problems with a large number of spatial points, the use of global basis
 functions makes the method very computationally expensive.
 For instance, the multiquadric function [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:multiquadric"

\end_inset

] actually grows larger as the distance from its center increases.
 The following is a method based on Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "chen-recent-2014"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for restricting the range of these global 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 functions by changing the solution variable of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 calculation from the coefficients of angular flux expansion to the angular
 flux itself at the basis and weight function centers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same strong-form equations with point cross section weighting [Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-point"

\end_inset

] are used for this discretization.
 This linear system can be localized by restricting the basis for each equation
 to a certain number of nearest neighbors, which creates a sparse matrix
 and a better-conditioned system.
 This would ordinarily create discontinuities in the solution where the
 basis functions end.
 However, if only the values at the basis function centers are needed, then
 the discontinuities do not present an issue.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{j}$
\end_inset

 be the set of the chosen nearest basis functions to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{x}_{j}$
\end_inset

, the basis function expansion [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:angular-expansion"

\end_inset

] becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{n,g}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right)=\sum_{i\in G_{j}}\alpha_{i,n,g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}\right).\label{eq:alternate-basis-expansion}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 be the sparse 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 matrix (or streaming operator) for each ordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and group 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, the linear system can be described by the equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{A}_{n,g}\bm{\alpha}_{n,g}=\bm{q}_{n,g}.\label{eq:alternate-strong-linear-system}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The values of the rows 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{a}_{j,n,g}$
\end_inset

 of the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{A}_{n,g}=\begin{bmatrix}\bm{a}_{1,n,g}^{\top}\\
\bm{a}_{2,n,g}^{\top}\\
\vdots\\
\bm{a}_{I,n,g}^{\top}
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:alternate-strong-matrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\bm{a}_{j,n,g}\right)_{i}=\begin{cases}
\mathcal{L}_{n,g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right), & \bm{x}_{j}\in V,\\
\mathcal{B}_{n,g}b_{i}\left(\bm{x}_{j}\right), & \bm{x}_{j}\in\partial V,
\end{cases}\label{eq:matrix-rows}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 is the boundary operator representing Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:strong-boundary-point"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are the boundary and interior of the spatial domain, respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:alternate-strong-linear-system"

\end_inset

 could be solved directly, but the matrix would be ill-conditioned due to
 the use of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 functions that may be very flat (see Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:introduction"

\end_inset

).
 Alternately, each row of this equation can be converted separately to produce
 a solution for the vector of angular flux values at the center points of
 the basis functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\psi}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

.
 The basis function expansion [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:alternate-basis-expansion"

\end_inset

] can be written as a linear system,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\psi}_{n,g}=\bm{\Gamma}_{j}\bm{\alpha}_{n,g},\label{eq:basis-vector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Gamma}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the basis function distance matrix for the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 local points for basis function 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 with indices 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bm{\Gamma}_{j}=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
b_{j_{1}}\left(\bm{x}_{j_{1}}\right) & \cdots & b_{j_{N}}\left(\bm{x}_{j_{1}}\right)\\
b_{j_{1}}\left(\bm{x}_{j_{2}}\right) & \cdots & b_{j_{N}}\left(\bm{x}_{j_{2}}\right)\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
b_{j_{1}}\left(\bm{x}_{j_{N}}\right) & \cdots & b_{j_{N}}\left(\bm{x}_{j_{N}}\right)
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

and where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\alpha}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 vector is appropriately indexed to be of the same size as the number of
 local points.
 Applying the inverse of this matrix to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:basis-vector"

\end_inset

, the equation for a single row of the matrix becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{a}_{j,n,g}^{\top}\bm{\alpha}_{n,g}=\bm{a}_{j,n,g}^{\top}\bm{\Gamma}_{j}^{-1}\bm{\psi}_{n,g}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

From these equations, the matrix describing the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{B}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\psi}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{b}_{j,n,g}=\left(\bm{a}_{j,n,g}^{\top}\bm{\Gamma}_{j}^{-1}\right)^{\top}=\left(\bm{\Gamma}_{j}^{\top}\right)^{-1}\bm{a}_{j,n,g},\label{eq:localized-row}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which converts the linear system of equations to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{B}_{n,g}\bm{\psi}_{n,g}=\bm{q}_{n,g}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Gamma}$
\end_inset

 matrix is the same for every group and direction, and so the LU decomposition
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Gamma}_{j}$
\end_inset

 matrix can be stored and reused, making the cost of inversion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Gamma}_{j}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{a}_{j,n,g}$
\end_inset

 comparable in time to the calculation of the values of the angular flux
 from the basis function expansion.
 The switch to a solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\psi}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 can produce a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{B}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 with a lower condition number than 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

, while the switch to a local basis makes the condition number for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Gamma}_{j}$
\end_inset

 lower than that of either 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{A}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{B}_{n,g}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As global 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

s are used in this section, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
gls{rbf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shape parameter is altered from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rbf-shape"

\end_inset

 to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{i}=\frac{k}{\Delta r},\label{eq:rbf-shape-global}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta r$
\end_inset

 is the average distance to the nearest points (two in 1D, four in 2D, six
 in 3D) and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a chosen constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compared to the weak-form equations or even for the strong-form equations
 presented in Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:transport-discretization"

\end_inset

, this discretization depends much more on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correct
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 choice of parameters to get a good solution.
 This discretization does successfully solve the slab geometry problem in
