\begin_layout Subsubsection
Additional scattering simplifications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The diffusion coefficient in Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffusion"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffusion-boundary"

\end_inset

 couples the diffusion operator in energy.
 Unlike the 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{N}$
\end_inset

 transport equation [Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:discrete-ordinates-transport"

\end_inset

], for which the advection operator can be inverted separately for each
 group, this means the inversion for the diffusion operator is also directly
 coupled.
 Through additional approximations, this limitation can be removed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If the diffusion coefficient matrix is made to be diagonal, the group-to-group
 dependence of the diffusion operator disappears.
 This matrix can be directly diagonalized or the off-diagonal elements of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Sigma}_{s;1}$
\end_inset

 can be neglected.
 In either case, with a diagonal diffusion matrix with diagonal values 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{g}=D_{g\to g}$
\end_inset

, Eqs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffusion"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diffusion-boundary"

\end_inset

 become 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
\frac{1}{v_{g}\left(\bm{x}\right)}\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Phi_{g}\left(\bm{x},t\right)-\bm{\nabla}\cdot D_{g}\left(\bm{x}\right)\bm{\nabla}\Phi_{g}\left(\bm{x},t\right)+\Sigma_{t;g}\left(\bm{x}\right)\Phi_{g}\left(\bm{x},t\right)\\
=\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\Sigma_{s;0,g'\to g}\left(\bm{x}\right)\Phi_{g'}\left(\bm{x},t\right)+\frac{\chi_{g}\left(\bm{x}\right)}{4\pi}\sum_{g'=1}^{G}\nu\Sigma_{f;g'}\left(\bm{x}\right)\Phi_{g'}\left(\bm{x},t\right)+Q_{0,g}\left(\bm{x},t\right),\\
\bm{x}\in V,\quad g=1,\dots,G,\quad0<t,\label{eq:diffusion-simplified}
